SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT
 THIS SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT ("Agreement") is made and entered into this December 16, 2021 (the "Effective Date"), by and between Indiana Crossroads Wind Farm LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Indiana Crossroads Wind I") and Meadow Lake Solar Park LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Indiana Crossroads Solar I").
RECITALS
A. Indiana Crossroads Wind I is developing and operating a wind generation facility located in White County, Indiana commonly referred to as the Indiana Crossroads Wind Farm (the "Indiana Crossroads Wind I Facility").
B. Indiana Crossroads Solar I is developing a solar generation facility located in White County, Indiana, commonly referred to as the Indiana Crossroads Solar Farm (the "Indiana Crossroads Solar I Facility"). The Indiana Crossroads Solar I Facility will be constructed adjacent to the Indiana Crossroads Wind I Facility.
C. The installed nameplate generating capacity of each of the Facilities is as follows:
Indiana Crossroads Wind I Facility:	302.4 MW
Indiana Crossroads Solar I Facility:	200 MW
D. Indiana Crossroads Wind I has designed and constructed, and owns, operates, and maintains the 345 kV transmission line to the point of interconnection at the 345kV Reynolds Substation in White County, Indiana and other associated facilities connecting the Indiana Crossroads Wind I Facility to the transmission system, all as more particularly described in Attachment B-1. The Shared Facilities have been constructed according to that certain Indiana Crossroads Wind Farm Turnkey Engineering, Procurement and Construction Contract, dated as of August 18, 2020, between Indiana Crossroads Wind I and White Construction, LLC.
E. Indiana Crossroads Wind I holds certain real property interests subject to the easement, lease, option or other rights and obligations in the documents described under the applicable section of Exhibit B. 
F. Subject to Section 4.1 herein, Indiana Crossroads Solar I desires to acquire partial ownership rights in the Shared Assets and Shared Real Property (both as defined below), from Indiana Crossroads Wind I to support Indiana Crossroads Solar I's development and construction of the Indiana Crossroads Solar I Facility, and to engage the Operator to operate, maintain, repair and manage the foregoing, all in accordance with and subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement.
 NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the recitals, the premises, covenants and conditions contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which the Co-Owners acknowledge, the Co-Owners agree as follows:

ARTICLE I -- DEFINITIONS, INTERPRETATIONS AND EXHIBITS
	1.1	Definitions. As used in this Agreement, including the Recitals, and except as required by
grammatical usage and apart from proper nouns, each capitalized term has the meaning given to it in this Agreement and in the Schedule of Definitions attached as Exhibit A. 
	1.2	Interpretation. In this Agreement, unless a clear, contrary intention appears: (a) the
singular includes the plural and vice versa; (b) reference to any Person includes such Person's successors and assigns but, in the case of a Co-Owner, only if such assigns are permitted by this Agreement, and reference to a Person in a particular capacity excludes such Person in any other capacity; (c) reference to any gender includes each other gender; (d) reference to any agreement (including this Agreement), document or instrument means such agreement, document or instrument as amended, restated, supplemented or modified and in effect from time to time in accordance with the terms thereof and, if applicable, the terms of this Agreement; (e) reference to any Law means such Law as amended, modified, codified, or reenacted, in whole or in part, and in effect from time to time, including, if applicable, rules and regulations promulgated thereunder; (f) reference to any Section means such Section of this Agreement, and references in any Section or definition to any clause means such clause of such Section or definition; (g) "hereunder," "hereof," "hereto" and words of similar import shall be deemed references to this Agreement as a whole and not to any particular Section or other provision of this Agreement; (h) "including" means including without limiting the generality of any description such term; and (i) relative to the determination of any period of time, "from" means "from and including", "to" means "to but excluding" and "through" means "through and including".
	1.3	Incorporation of Recitals and Exhibits. The Recitals set forth in this Agreement and the
Exhibits and Attachments attached hereto are incorporated into this Agreement by reference for all purposes.
ARTICLE II -- TERM OF AGREEMENT
	2.1	Term. This Agreement shall become effective as of the Effective Date and shall remain in
force and effect until the earlier of (a) the date that is fifty (50) years after the Effective Date; (b) the retirement and final disposition of all components of the Shared Facilities; (c) the date that Indiana Crossroads Solar I terminates this Agreement pursuant to Section 4.1.3 herein and (d) the date that the Co-Owners unanimously agree to terminate this Agreement.
	2.2	Payments on Termination. Upon termination of this Agreement, each Co-Owner shall pay
Operator for its share, in proportion to its Undivided Use Interest at the time of such termination as set forth herein this Agreement, of any remaining balance owed for Operator's costs incurred or irrevocably committed to be incurred pursuant to this Agreement as of the date of termination, within sixty (60) days following receipt of an invoice from Operator requiring such payment; provided that Operator shall use commercially reasonable efforts to minimize such costs.
	2.3	Survival. Any obligations of one Co-Owner to another, including payment obligations and
indemnity obligations, as a result of this Agreement which accrued prior to or as a result of termination of this Agreement shall survive termination of this Agreement.

ARTICLE III -- SHARED FACILITIES AND REAL PROPERTY
	3.1	Shared Facilities. The Co-Owners plan to procure, install and construct, or have procured,
installed and constructed, certain facilities for electrical transmission, communications structures and other facilities, as described in Attachment B-1, which may be altered or reconstructed by amendment in accordance with this Agreement, for shared use by the Co-Owners (collectively, the "Shared Facilities"). Each grouping of Shared Facilities is described in Exhibit B (each a "Shared Facilities Group").
	3.2	Shared Real Property. The Shared Facilities in each Shared Facilities Group are or will be
located on certain real property (collectively, the "Shared Real Property") that is subject to the easement, lease, option or other rights and obligations in the documents described under the applicable section of Exhibit B (collectively, the "Shared Real Property Agreements").
	3.3	Shared Assets Groups. Each Shared Facilities Group, combined with the Shared Real
Property corresponding to the Shared Facilities in such Shared Facilities Group ("Shared Assets") described under the same section in Exhibit B shall be referred to herein as a "Shared Assets Group".
	3.4	Access. Each Co-Owner shall have a non-exclusive right of access (a) to the Shared
Facilities in which it has an Undivided Use Interest as necessary in order to ensure that Operator is meeting its obligations with respect to operation, maintenance and repair of such Shared Facilities, that Co-Owner's Facility remains operational, and for the purposes contemplated in Article VII; (b) to make any necessary repairs to such Shared Facilities not timely made by Operator or in the event of an Emergency Condition; (c) to exercise any of its rights with respect to the Shared Facilities under this Agreement (including the inspection and testing rights under Section 5.2) and (d) over any Shared Real Property in which such Co-Owner has an Ownership Interest; provided that, subject to the provisions of Section 13.1.4, if such Co-Owner is not the Operator, it shall (i) provide reasonable notice to Operator, and (ii) not unreasonably interfere with Operator's operation, maintenance or repair of the Shared Facilities or of another Co-Owner's Facility.
ARTICLE IV -- OWNERSHIP OF AND RIGHT TO USE SHARED ASSETS
	4.1	Undivided Ownership Interests. 
 4.1.1 Notice to Acquire. In the event that Indiana Crossroads Solar I desires to proceed with the continued development and construction of the Indiana Crossroads Solar I Facility and so long as the condition precedent set forth in Section 4.3(a) has been satisfied, Indiana Crossroads Solar I shall, at its sole discretion, send a written notice to Indiana Crossroads Wind I stating its desire to proceed with the consummation of the Ownership Interest Acquisition (as defined below) (the "Notice to Acquire").
 4.1.2 Ownership Interest Acquisition. Following Indiana Crossroads Wind I's receipt of the Notice to Acquire, as soon as reasonably practical, but in any event no earlier than six months prior to the projected commencement of commercial operation of the Indiana Crossroads Solar I Facility, the Co-Owners shall (A) execute the Bill of Sale; (B) execute the Real Property Assignment and Assumption Agreement and, if applicable (but, for the avoidance of doubt, not in connection with Indiana Crossroads Solar I's Ownership Interest Acquisition), the Warranty Deed and (C) amend this Agreement as reasonably required to accurately reflect the Shared Facilities (the "Ownership Interest Acquisition"), pursuant to which each Co-Owner shall own
3
DM_US 183725589-12.090026.0055

an undivided interest, as a tenant-in-common, in the applicable Shared Assets Group (and equal to its Proportionate Share as set forth and described in Exhibit C in such applicable Shared Assets Group (such undivided interest of each Co-Owner being referred to in this Agreement as its "Ownership Interest"). NOTWITHSTANDING ANYTHING HEREIN TO THE CONTRARY (EXCEPT WITH RESPECT TO SECTION 6.2), INDIANA CROSSROADS WIND I SHALL HAVE NO LIABILITY TO ANY OTHER CO-OWNER FOR ANY DEFECT IN THE DESIGN, CONSTRUCTION OR UTILITY OF ANY OF THE SHARED FACILITIES. EXCEPT AS SET FORTH IN SECTION 6.2, INDIANA CROSSROADS WIND I MAKES NO REPRESENTATIONS OR WARRANTIES OF ANY KIND WITH RESPECT TO THE CONDITION, USE OR FITNESS OF ANY OF THE SHARED REAL PROPERTY OR WITH RESPECT TO THE DESIGN, CONSTRUCTION, OPERATION OR UTILITY OF ANY OF THE SHARED FACILITIES AND HEREBY DISCLAIMS ANY WARRANTY OF MERCHANTABILITY OR FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE OR ANY OTHER WARRANTY OF ANY KIND WITH RESPECT TO THE SHARED REAL PROPERTY OR THE SHARED ASSETS. The Co-Owners agree they will look solely to the designers, contractors, suppliers, manufacturers and other Persons who participated in the design and/or construction of the Shared Facilities with respect to any defects or breaches of contract or warranty.
 4.1.3 Indiana Crossroads Solar I Termination Notice. Prior to the commencement of the Ownership Interest Acquisition, if no Additional Phases have been joined to this Agreement in accordance with Section 4.4, in the event that Indiana Crossroads Solar I desires to cease the development of the Indiana Crossroads Solar I Facility, at its sole discretion, Indiana Crossroads Solar I shall send written notice to Indiana Crossroads Wind I of its decision to terminate this Agreement (the "Termination Notice"). Upon Indiana Crossroads Wind I's receipt of the Termination Notice this Agreement shall automatically terminate and no Co-Owner shall have any further liability or obligation to the other Co-Owner hereunder.
4.2	Undivided Use Interests. Each Co-Owner who has an Ownership Interest in a Shared
Assets Group shall have an undivided right to the use or capacity of the applicable Shared Assets equal to its Proportionate Share therein, effective on and after the date that all conditions precedent set forth in Section 4.3 below applicable to such Co-Owner (if any) are satisfied (the "CP Satisfaction Date") (once effective, such undivided use interest of a Co-Owner is referred to in this Agreement as its "Undivided Use Interest"). Each Co-Owner's Proportionate Share in its Shared Assets Group is set forth on Exhibit C, which may be revised from time to time in accordance with this Agreement.
 4.2.1 Generator Lead Line. Each Co-Owner of a Generator Lead Line shall be entitled to use its Undivided Use Interest in the Delivery Capability of the Generator Lead Line. In the event that the Delivery Capability of the Generator Lead Line exceeds the capability provided in the applicable Interconnection Agreement, with Transmission Owner's and Transmission Provider's consent and approval, each Co-Owner's Undivided Use Interest will be increased pro rata in accordance with its Ownership Interest for so long as the Delivery Capability is in excess of the capability provided in the Interconnection Agreements. For the avoidance of doubt, the Co-Owners will not exceed the Maximum Facility Output, as defined in the applicable Interconnection Agreement, unless all necessary approvals and consents are obtained (including from Transmission Owner and Transmission Provider).

 4.2.2 Excess Capability. No Co-Owner shall have the right to use more than its Proportionate Share (ignoring, for this purpose, clause (i) of the proviso in the definition of "Proportionate Share") of the Delivery Capability of the Generator Lead Line or portion of the Generator Lead Line. During periods in which a Co-Owner is not utilizing its full Undivided Use Interest in the Delivery Capability of the Generator Lead Line or portion of Generator Lead Line, the other Co-Owner may utilize more than its full Undivided Use Interest, subject to the operating limits of the Shared Facilities, so long as such usage does not interfere with or adversely affect the first Co-Owner's energy schedules and deliveries; and provided that (i) prior to any Co-Owner using more than its Proportionate Share of the Delivery Capability of the Generator Lead Line or portion of the Generator Lead Line, the Co-Owners shall have obtained all necessary Governmental Authority authorizations, including FERC acceptance for filing of an effective transmission services agreement for such usage to the extent required and (ii) no payment obligation will attach to such utilization by a Co-Owner of more than its full Undivided Use Interest.
	4.3	Conditions Precedent. The CP Satisfaction Date with respect to Indiana Crossroads Solar
I shall be the date on which all of the following have occurred: (a) sixty (60) calendar days have elapsed since Indiana Crossroads Solar I was granted both (i) a final order from the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) pursuant to Section 205 of the Federal Power Act, as amended, authorizing the sale at wholesale of electric energy, capacity and ancillary services at market based rates, accepting a tariff providing for such sales and granting such waivers and blanket authorizations as are customarily granted by FERC and (ii) a final order from the Indiana Utility Regulatory Commission approving the transfer of Indiana Crossroads Solar I's Proportionate Share of the Shared Assets, (b) the Ownership Interest Acquisition shall have occurred, (c) this Agreement shall have been amended to incorporate Part II of Attachment B-2 in accordance with Section 5.1, and (d) no Event of Default shall have occurred and be continuing with respect to Indiana Crossroads Solar I. For the avoidance of doubt, there shall be no conditions precedent to the CP Satisfaction Date with respect to Indiana Crossroads Wind I, and such CP Satisfaction Date shall be deemed to have occurred on the Commissioning Date with respect to the Indiana Crossroads Wind I Facility.
	4.4	Additional Phases. Subject to the unanimous written consent of all of the Co-Owners, not
to be unreasonably withheld, a Co-Owner or its Affiliate, or an EDP Renewables North America subsidiary, shall have the right to build and operate an additional phase or phases (an "Additional Phase"), to connect such Additional Phase (or such portion of the Additional Phase as may be compatible with Transmission Owner's interconnection facilities), to the Shared Facilities and to use the Shared Assets, subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement. If the Co-Owners provide their unanimous written consent, the owner of such Additional Phase shall execute a joinder, the form of which is attached as Exhibit H hereto (the "Joinder"), and the Co-Owners shall execute an appropriate amendment to this Agreement to reflect the acquisition of the Undivided Use Interest of the Additional Phase in the applicable Shared Assets Groups. Notwithstanding anything contained herein to the contrary, the owner of the Additional Phase shall bear any incremental costs and expenses of modifying and upgrading the applicable existing Shared Facilities to accommodate the connection of its Facility.
	4.5	Operator-Initiated Curtailment. 
 4.5.1 The Operator in its reasonable discretion may interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power through the Shared Facilities: (i) if it determines, in its reasonable discretion and in accordance with Good Utility Practice, that interruption or reduction is necessary due to an
5

Emergency Condition; or (ii) at the direction of the Transmission Owner or Transmission Provider pursuant to rights under the Interconnection Agreements, MISO rules or otherwise required by Applicable Law. The Operator will use commercially reasonable efforts to give the Co-Owners as much advance notice as is reasonably possible of such interruptions, reductions, or curtailments.
 4.5.2 With respect to any interruption or reduction of deliveries of electrical power pursuant to Section 4.5.1, the Operator shall limit the length of any such interruption or curtailment to the minimum extent and minimum time strictly necessary to correct the problem and, to the extent commercially reasonable, during periods of low or no generation or low energy prices.
 4.5.3 To the extent that the need for any curtailment, interruption or reduction can be attributed to a particular Co-Owner's Facility or portions of its Facility or the failure of such Facility to comply with the order to curtail or a default by such Co-Owner under this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreements or any power purchase agreement, or to the extent such Co-Owner's Facility is the cause of an Emergency Condition or is directed by Transmission Provider or the Transmission Owner to curtail, then (A) after the Construction Period of such Facility, such curtailment shall be allocated first to such Co-Owner and such Co-Owner will be responsible for all damages under any Claims, incurred or sustained by the other Co-Owner, resulting from such curtailment (subject to the limitations in this Agreement), and (B) at all times, the other Co-Owner shall reasonably cooperate with the Operator and the Co-Owner whose Facility is the cause of such condition to limit the curtailment to such Facility or such portions of the Facility, as the case may be.
4.6	Outage, Curtailment or Disconnection Generally. Each Co-Owner shall use commercially
reasonable efforts to avoid, or minimize the scope and duration of, any outage, curtailment, or disconnection of the Shared Facilities, to provide prompt (or, if known in advance, prior) notice to the Operator and the other Co-Owner of any such event, and to cooperate with the Operator and the other Co-Owner to minimize any damages that may be suffered by the other Co-Owner as a result of any such event, recognizing that a Co-Owner shall be entitled (provided that such Co-Owner otherwise complies with the requirements of this Section 4.6) to cause an outage, curtailment, or disconnection of the Shared Facilities for such limited time and scope as may be necessary for the construction, installation, interconnection and/or startup of such Co-Owner's Facility.
 4.6.1 Except as set forth in Section 4.6.2, to the extent that any Co-Owner's Facility is disconnected, incurs any downtime in excess of 48 hours in any calendar year, or experiences an unscheduled outage or grid-ordered curtailment required by the Transmission Provider or Transmission Owner, or has its Interconnection Agreement terminated, in any such case resulting in a loss of production or revenue to such Facility, and in any such case arising from another Co-Owner's actions or inactions (including any scheduled maintenance by a Co-Owner pursuant to Section 6.4) (each a "Co-Owner Curtailment Event") then, in any such case without limiting a Party's indemnification obligations under Article XV, the responsible Co-Owner shall reimburse the other Co-Owner for the applicable Net Revenue Losses within thirty (30) days of receipt of the invoice. The Co-Owner requesting reimbursement shall provide documentation to the other Co-Owner for the period of such disconnection, downtime, curtailment or outage, as applicable.

 4.6.2 If in connection with the Construction Period of a BTA Project, (A) the Transmission Owner or Transmission Provider directs the Co-Owner of such BTA Project to curtail or disconnect the Shared Facilities, (B) such Co-Owner provides reasonable advance notice of such curtailment or disconnection and (C) the length of any such interruption or curtailment is limited to the minimum extent and minimum time strictly necessary, then the Co-Owner of such BTA Project shall not be required to pay the other Co-Owners for any lost revenue associated with such downtime or curtailment (it being understood, for the avoidance of doubt, that any curtailment or disconnection after the Construction Period shall be governed by Sections 4.5 and 4.6.1).
ARTICLE V -- METERING, MEASUREMENT OF ENERGY DELIVERIES AND LOSSES
	5.1	Measurement of Energy and Allocation of Losses. Energy transmitted on the applicable
Generator Lead Line shall be measured and allocated between the Co-Owners of the Shared Facilities as set forth on Attachment B-2 (the "Revenue Metering Report and Diagram"). The Revenue Metering Report and Diagram depicts and delineates several metering connections used to measure energy and allocate losses by and among the Facilities, and such metering calculations are used to determine the Facilities' generated real power delivered to and received from the point of interconnect. Part II of Attachment B-2 shall be mutually agreed upon by the Parties in writing, upon which the Parties shall amend this Agreement in accordance with Section 17.5 to incorporate such agreed-upon Metering Report into Attachment B-2 as Part II thereof.
	5.2	Testing and Repair of Co-Owner's Meters. 
 5.2.1 Inspection and Testing. If applicable and in conformance with the applicable Interconnection Agreement(s), a Co-Owner will cause meters (other than revenue meters owned by the interconnection provider and check meters owned by the individual Co-Owner) to be inspected and tested upon its installation and at least once every twenty four (24) months thereafter, or more frequently if required by MISO rules, by the Interconnection Agreement or by any power purchase agreement to which a Co-Owner is a party, and at any other reasonable time upon the other Co-Owner's request. The Co-Owner requesting such inspection and testing will pay the costs of same, unless the results of the test show the Co-Owner's meter to be inaccurate by more than half of one percent (0.5%), in which case the Co-Owners will share the costs of the test. Each Co-Owner will give the other Co-Owners reasonable advance notice of tests of its meter and the other Co-Owners have the right to witness such tests.
 5.2.2 Calibration or Repair. If a test shows a Co-Owner's meter to be inaccurate, the owner or owners of the meter will use reasonable efforts to cause its meter to be calibrated, repaired or replaced as soon as reasonably practical. Such adjustments shall be reflected as charges or credits, as applicable, on the invoices for O&M Services rendered monthly by Operator to the Co-Owners.
ARTICLE VI -- OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF SHARED FACILITIES.
	6.1	Engagement of Operator. The Co-Owners hereby engage the Operator to manage, operate,
maintain and repair the Shared Facilities and to perform other duties pertaining to the Shared Assets (the "O&M Services"), all as set forth in this Agreement. The Operator accepts such engagement and agrees to perform such duties in accordance with the terms and conditions hereof. Co-Owners acknowledge and agree that EDP Renewables North America LLC provides certain services (pursuant to the Management
7
DM_US 183725589-12.090026.0055

Services Agreement, dated June 18, 2021, between Operator and EDP Renewables North America LLC) with respect to the NERC Reliability Standards on their behalf and is the registered entity as of the Effective Date.
	6.2	Standards for Operator's Performance. Operator shall perform or cause to performed the
O&M Services in accordance with Good Utility Practice, the Material Project Agreements, the Shared Real Property Agreements, this Agreement and all Applicable Laws and requirements of Governmental Authorities, including without limitation all Hazardous Materials Laws and all Environmental Laws, and all safety policies and procedures (collectively, the "Performance Standard").
	6.3	O&M Services. The Operator shall provide or cause to be provided the following services
on behalf of each of the Co-Owners who have an Undivided Use Interest from and after the date such Co-Owner has notified Operator of its exercised right to an Undivided Use Interest in the Shared Assets pursuant to Section 4.2: 
(a) manage, supervise, operate, repair and maintain the Shared Assets, including the day to day management of the Shared Assets in accordance with Material Project Agreements Good Utility Practice and the Annual O&M Budget;
(b) pay and collect amounts due in connection with the Shared Assets including but not limited to taxes and assessments pursuant to Section 12.2, and maintain one or more bank accounts wherein funds received by the Operator in connection with its duties herein shall be maintained;
(c) expend monies necessary for the management, operation, maintenance and repair of the Shared Facilities;
(d) notify every Co-Owner of any notice (or any other information reasonably anticipated to affect the Co-Owners) received by the Operator or received from any Co-Owner;
(e) manage compliance with the Co-Owners' rights in Shared Real Property in accordance with the Shared Real Property Agreements, including making payments required thereunder; provided that the Operator shall have no right to amend such rights in the Shared Real Property; and
(f) with respect to the Shared Real Property and the Shared Facilities located on the Shared Real Property, oversee all investigations, studies, clean up, corrective action or response or remedial action required by any Governmental Authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to the use, operation or ownership of the Shared Real Property or the Shared Facilities located on the Shared Real Property.
	6.4	Scheduled Maintenance. Operator shall schedule, or cause to be scheduled, maintenance
and any planned outages of the Shared Facilities so as to minimize interference with Co-Owners' scheduled energy deliveries. Maintenance and any planned outages of the Shared Facilities shall be scheduled, to the maximum extent possible, during scheduled maintenance outages of the Co-Owners' Facilities. Each Co-Owner will provide to the Operator and the other affected Co-Owners by January 1 of each year commencing with January 1, 2023 a proposed schedule of planned maintenance for the
8
DM_US 183725589-12.090026.0055

subsequent twelve-month period that is expected to require an outage or otherwise would reasonably be expected to cause an adverse impact to the Shared Facilities. An affected Co-Owner may notify the other Co-Owner in writing of any request for changes to the schedule of planned maintenance outages. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, all scheduled outages of the Shared Facilities (including any outage resulting from scheduled maintenance outages of any Co-Owner's Facilities that are expected to require a Shared Facilities outage or otherwise would reasonably be expected to cause an adverse impact to the Shared Facilities) will be determined in the sole discretion of Indiana Crossroads Wind I; provided that Operator will use reasonable efforts to limit the duration of any outage, planned or unplanned, consistent with the Performance Standard.
	6.5	Unplanned Outages. Operator will notify, or cause to be notified, Co-Owners of all
emergency or unplanned outages of any of the Shared Facilities as soon as practicable, in accordance with Good Utility Practice, and will provide an estimated time of return of the Shared Facilities to service, or if not known, will keep, or cause to be kept, Co-Owners advised regarding the status of same.
	6.6	Emergency Conditions. In the event of an emergency condition involving the Shared
Assets that could be reasonably expected by Operator to result in possible personal injury, loss of life, damage to or destruction of property, or danger to the public (an "Emergency Condition"), the Operator shall, without the need for prior notification of the Co-Owners, take such action, or cause such action, as may be reasonable and necessary, as determined in the sole discretion of the Operator, to prevent, avoid or mitigate such loss, and shall, as soon as reasonably practicable, report any such emergency, including the Operator's response thereto, to the Co-Owners, and Operator, if allowed by law, be compensated by the Co-Owners for the costs of taking such actions in proportion to their Ownership Interest in the Shared Assets so affected.
	6.7	O&M Costs. Costs of performing O&M Services (the "O&M Costs") shall be budgeted
in accordance with Section 6.8 and include all payments made and expenses incurred by Operator in performing O&M Services (at cost and without markup), including but not limited to related overhead and applicable taxes, and costs (except insurance costs) related to ownership of the Shared Assets.
	6.8	Budgeting Process. Commencing in November 2022 and each subsequent year during the
term of this Agreement, Operator will prepare a forecast budget of O&M Costs for the following calendar year and will provide a copy to the Co-Owners by November 15th. Co-Owners will have thirty (30) days thereafter to review the forecast budget and discuss any concerns with the forecast budget with Operator. Operator's implementation of the O&M Services consistent with the forecast budget is subject to Co-Owners' prior approval within such 30-day period, not to be unreasonably withheld; provided that following the 30-day period such forecast budget of O&M Costs shall be deemed approved if no concerns are identified in writing by the Co-Owners (such approved or deemed approved forecast budget, the "Annual O&M Budget"). In the event that the Annual O&M Budget for the next succeeding year is not approved by the Co-Owners prior to the commencement of such year, the Annual O&M Budget for the then current year shall remain in effect for the subsequent year until a new Annual O&M Budget is approved. The Annual O&M Budget shall include allocated costs and expenses to each Shared Assets Group to the extent reasonably practical.
	6.9	Extraordinary Maintenance. Each Co-Owner agrees to reimburse Operator for its share,
in proportion to its Undivided Use Interest, of the costs of any maintenance or other services required in the event of unusual or catastrophic circumstances, to the extent such costs were not included in the forecast budget for O&M Services and incurred by the Operator ("Extraordinary Maintenance").
9
DM_US 183725589-12.090026.0055

 6.10 Responsibility for O&M Costs. Each Co-Owner shall be responsible for its share, in proportion to its Undivided Use Interest, of O&M Costs, including its share of the costs of any Extraordinary Maintenance incurred by Operator, which shall be invoiced by Operator on a quarterly basis, on or before the tenth (10th) day following the end of each calendar quarter. The invoices shall be delivered to the parties identified in Section 17.15. Co-Owners shall pay such invoice within thirty (30) days of its receipt (the "Due Date"). Any amounts not paid by the Due Date shall be deemed delinquent and shall accrue interest at the then-effective prime rate of interest published under "Money Rates" by The Wall Street Journal, plus two percent per annum from the Due Date to the date of payment (the "Late Payment Rate"). For purposes of this Section 6.10 and for Section 6.11, "receipt" shall mean the date upon which the invoice is received in accordance with Section 17.15. In the event that any Due Date falls upon a weekend day or bank holiday, such payment shall be due and payable on the first Business Day immediately thereafter.
 6.11 Disputes. If a Co-Owner disputes the accuracy of all or any portion of an invoice, such Co-Owner shall, nevertheless, pay the undisputed portion of the amount owing on the invoice and submit to Operator a written statement detailing the items and amount disputed. If Co-Owner and Operator are unable to resolve the disputed items, the matter will be resolved in accordance with the dispute resolution provisions in Exhibit D. DISPUTE RESOLUTION PROCEDURES
1. Consideration by the Authorized Representatives. 
 All questions concerning interpretation of this Agreement, the acceptable fulfillment of the Co-Owners' respective obligations hereunder, as well as all other questions regarding this Agreement in each case that cannot readily be resolved by the Co-Owners shall be resolved in accordance with this Exhibit D. In the event that the authorized representatives of the Co-Owners cannot reach agreement on any question arising under this Agreement, such dispute shall be referred to senior officers of the Co-Owners pursuant to Paragraph 2 below.
2. Negotiations by Senior Officers. 
 Any disputes arising pursuant to this Agreement that cannot be resolved by the authorized representatives of the Co-Owners within fourteen (14) days after receipt of notice of such dispute (specifically referencing this Exhibit D) shall be referred to the vice president or other senior officer of each of the Co-Owners having executive responsibility for such Co-Owner's Facility. If such senior officers, negotiating in good faith, fail to reach an agreement within a reasonable period of time, not exceeding twenty (20) days after such referral, then any Co-Owner to such dispute may institute proceedings as set forth in Paragraph 3 below.
3. Formal Dispute Resolution. 
 (a) If a dispute described in Paragraph 2 is not resolved by the executive management of the Co-Owners, the Co-Owners shall engage in non-binding mediation of such dispute. Such mediation shall be conducted (i) in Indianapolis, Indiana, (ii) within thirty (30) days of a Co-Owner instituting dispute resolution under this Paragraph 3, (iii) by a single, impartial mediator who is selected by the mutual agreement of the Co-Owners, and (iv) in accordance with such procedures as may be adopted by such mediator. Such mediation shall not, without the express agreement of the Co-Owners at the time, extend for a period of more than two (2) days. Each Co-Owner may be represented by persons of such Co-Owner's choice during such mediation. Nothing herein shall be deemed to grant any mediator the authority to impose a resolution of any dispute being mediated. Any information introduced, proposals made or positions taken in the mediation shall be deemed to be confidential and for settlement purposes only and may not be introduced by the other Co-Owner in any subsequent litigation of the matters subject to mediation. The Co- Owners shall share the costs of the mediator, including any fees and meeting room rentals.
 (b) If a dispute described in Paragraph 2 is not resolved by the executive management of the Co-Owners and the Co-Owners have not otherwise resolved such dispute through mediation pursuant to Paragraph 3(a), a Co-Owner may submit the matter at issue for resolution in an action brought before the courts of the State of Indiana in the County of White or in the United States District Court for the Northern District of Indiana, which courts shall have nonexclusive jurisdiction with respect to such matters. Net Revenue Loss Calculation Methodology
Net Revenue Loss payments ("NRL Payments") during any period of time for which they are required hereunder (the "NRL Period") shall equal the sum of :
 (a) the product of (i) the Curtailed MWhs multiplied by (ii) the price or prices for which such electricity would have been sold by the Co-Owner receiving such NRL Payment under such Co-Owner's power purchase agreement(s) had the electricity been produced, or if such Co-Owner has no power purchase agreement or the Curtailed MWhs would not have been sold under any such power purchase agreement, then at the simple average of the real-time settlement point prices for energy based on the specified prices at node NIPS.INCROSWF, stated in Dollars per MWh, as reported by MISO for all settlement intervals during such NRL Period;
 (b) if the Co-Owner or any of its Investors is eligible to receive the federal production tax credits pursuant to 26 U.S.C. 45, the product of (i) the Curtailed MWhs multiplied by (ii) as of any date of calculation, the PTC Value plus a tax gross-up amount and shall be calculated as follows: PTC Value / (1 - the Highest Marginal Rate). For purposes of this formula, "PTC Value" means Twenty-Five Dollars ($25.00) for each MWh (the 2021 amount), as such dollar amount shall be adjusted each subsequent year for inflation consistent with the adjustment to production tax credits under Section 45(b)(2) of the Code;
 (c) if the Co-Owner is eligible to receive renewable energy credits, including those granted pursuant to law, regulation, certification, markets, trading, off-set, private transaction, renewable portfolio standards, or voluntary programs, ("RECs"), the dollar value for the RECs that would have been payable to the Co-Owner receiving such NRL Payments during the NRL Period based on the average price per MWh of RECs of two valid seller price quotes for lots of not less than 5,000 MWhs of comparable RECs from nationally recognized REC brokers during such NRL Period; provided such Co-Owner is not otherwise compensated for RECs as part of subsection (a) above; and
 (d) any penalties or liquidated damages assessed against such Co-Owner for failing to produce electricity such Co-Owner was contractually obligated to produce or for failing to meet any availability or capacity requirements such Co-Owner was contractually obligated to meet.
For purposes of this Exhibit I, "Curtailed MWhs" shall mean either:
 (a) in the case that the Co-Owner receiving such NRL Payment is a wind generation facility, the number of MWhs that could have been produced during such calendar year but for each applicable Co-Owner Curtailment Event. Such calculation shall be (i) based on then-current wind turbine availability, wind turbine power curves, and wind speeds during the NRL Period and (ii) either reasonably acceptable to the Parties or confirmed by an independent engineer reasonably acceptable to the Parties; or
 (b) in the case that the Co-Owner receiving such NRL Payment is a solar generation facility, the number of MWhs that could have been produced during such calendar year but for
